
for RHEL, CentOS, Amazon Linux : "sudo yum install java -y"
for Ububtu: "sudo apt install java -ya"

Follow below for the current version:
sudo yum install httpd -y -- defaullt apache in linux library
sudo service httpd start -- start apache
ps -ef ! grep httpd --  to control apache httpd service is running or not

Follow below for the old version:
Package:
apache-tomcat-8.5.69.tar.gz
wget url
Extract file
tar -zxvf apache-tomcat-8.5.69.tar.gz -- zip file, extract, verbose, file


RHEL or CentOS:
yum install (package name)
yum remove (package name)
yum update (package name)
yum info (package name)
yum list available
yum list installed

Exapmles:
yum install unzip -y
yum install telnet -y
yum install wget -y
yum remove whet -y
yum update tree -y
yum info unzip
yum list installed
yum list installed l grep tree
yum list available 1 grep wget

Ubuntu ve Debian base distros:
sudo apt update  --> updating the package index (doesn't install/uninstall/update any package)
sudo apt install apache2  --> installing or updating a package named apache2
sudo apt list --upgradable  --> listing all upgradable packages
sudo apt full-upgrade  --> upgrading all applications
sudo apt full-upgrade -y   -->  assume yes to any prompt (useful in scripts)
sudo apt remove apache2  --> removing a package
sudo apt purge apache2  --> removing a package and its configurations
sudo apt autoremove  -->  removing dependencies that are not needed anymore
sudo apt clean  --> removing the saved deb files from the cache directory (var/cache/apt/archives)
sudo apt list  --> listing all available packages
sudo apt list | wc -l --> listing all available packages number
sudo apt list | grep nginx  --> searching for a package
sudo apt show nginx  --> showing information about a package
sudo apt list --installed  --> listing all installed packages
